<li id="cite_note-25"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-25">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation news">Flood, Alison (2014-08-21). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/aug/21/charles-dickens-george-eliot-a-tale-of-two-cities">"Charles Dickens novel inscribed to George Eliot up for sale"</a>. <i>The Guardian</i>. <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Serial_Number" title="International Standard Serial Number">ISSN</a>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.worldcat.org/issn/0261-3077">0261-3077</a><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">2017-01-29</span></span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Guardian&amp;rft.atitle=Charles+Dickens+novel+inscribed+to+George+Eliot+up+for+sale&amp;rft.date=2014-08-21&amp;rft.issn=0261-3077&amp;rft.aulast=Flood&amp;rft.aufirst=Alison&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theguardian.com%2Fbooks%2F2014%2Faug%2F21%2Fcharles-dickens-george-eliot-a-tale-of-two-cities&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AList+of+best-selling+books" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-26"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-26">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><i><a href="/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings" title="The Lord of the Rings">The Lord of the Rings</a></i> is considered by most people to be a single book, because it was written and planned by the author to be such. It is written in the preface to many editions that the book is sometimes 'erroneously' referred to as a trilogy, and goes on to state that it is one book in three volumes. Some people consider it to instead be a trilogy or series of three books, because it was originally published as a series of three volumes: <i><a href="/wiki/The_Fellowship_of_the_Ring" title="The Fellowship of the Ring">The Fellowship of the Ring</a></i>, <i><a href="/wiki/The_Two_Towers" title="The Two Towers">The Two Towers</a></i>, and <i><a href="/wiki/The_Return_of_the_King" title="The Return of the King">The Return of the King</a></i>. <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.waterstones.com/waterstonesweb/displayProductDetails.do?sku=5007234"><i>Lord of the Rings</i></a> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20070928071938/http://www.waterstones.com/waterstonesweb/displayProductDetails.do?sku=5007234">Archived</a> 2007-09-28 at the <a href="/wiki/Wayback_Machine" title="Wayback Machine">Wayback Machine</a>., Waterstones.com: This move by the publishing house was due largely to post-war paper shortages as well as to minimize the price of the first volume to aid sales.<br />
Wagner, Vit. <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/article/203389">"Tolkien proves he's still the king"</a>, <i><a href="/wiki/The_Toronto_Star" class="mw-redirect" title="The Toronto Star">The Toronto Star</a></i>, 16 April 2007: In subsequent printings the book has sometimes appeared as a single volume, and in at least one case was split into seven. The figure of 150 million is a 2007 estimate of copies of the full story sold, whether published as one volume, three, or some other configuration.</span></li>
